            <div></div>
          </div>

          <div class="learn__post__content">
            <p>
              Line charts are good for plotting data captured in a sequence,
              whether that sequence is the passage of time, or steps in a
              process or flow. These charts are typically used to plot a time
              series (also known as a run chart): a set of markers connected by
              lines, with the x axis showing the passage of time and the y axis
              plotting the value of a metric at each moment.
            </p>

            <h2 id="how-to-create-a-line-chart">How to create a line chart</h2>

            <p>
              Lets take a look at the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
              > table in the <a href="/glossary/sample-database"
                >Sample Database</a
              > that ships with Metabase. From the main navigation bar, click on
              <strong>+ New</strong> &gt; <strong>Question</strong>, which will
              take you to Metabases query builder. Choose <strong
                >Raw Data</strong
              > &gt; <strong>Sample Database</strong>, then pick the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Orders</code
              > table. Click <strong>Visualize</strong>, then click the <strong
                >Visualization button</strong
              > in the bottom right to bring up the <strong
                >Visualization sidebar</strong
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/orders-table.png"
                alt="The orders table"
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              Lets start with how <em>not</em> to create a line chart. If you select
              <strong>line chart</strong>, Metabase will present you with an
              empty line chart.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/empty-line-chart.png"
                alt="An empty line chart, before setting the x and y axes."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              Metabase cant read minds (yet), so it doesnt know which columns
              from the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >Orders</code
              > table to use for the x and y axes. To create a line chart, youll
              need to pick a metric for Metabase to plot over time. For example,
              you could show order totals over time by setting the x axis to <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">created_at</code
              > and the y axis to <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">total</code
              >. Metabase will automatically plot the line chart:
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/created-at-total.png"
                alt="A noisy line chart after setting the x and y axes, without first summarizing the data."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              Thats technically a line chart, but it looks more like the
              cardiograph of a startled hummingbird, and thats even after
              Metabase has truncated the results shown. (If you hover over the
              gray warning triangle in the upper right, youll see that Metabase
              has only plotted 2,000 rows.)
            </p>

            <p>
              To make the chart more legible, we can summarize the data, so each
              point on the line chart is an aggregate of rowsbuckets of
              records. (Its much more common to plot unaggregated rows in
              visualizations like <a
                href="/docs/latest/questions/visualizations/map">pin maps</a
              >, or a <a
                href="/docs/latest/questions/visualizations/visualizing-results#scatterplots-and-bubble-charts"
                >scatterplot</a
              >, e.g., to show each product plotted by price and rating.)
            </p>

            <p>
              As an example of an aggregated metric, lets plot the sum of order
              totals for each month. Click on the green <strong
                >Summarize button</strong
              > to pull up the <strong>Summarize sidebar</strong>. Metabase
              defaults to counting the records, but were not interested in the
              number of orders, so well click on <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Count</code
              > and change it to <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Sum of</code
              > and select the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Total</code
              > column from <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"
                >Order</code
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              Next, well want to group our order totals by month. In the <strong
                >Group by</strong
              > section, under <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Order</code
              >, mouse over the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Created At</code
              > field click on the <code
                class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">+</code
              > button to add the grouping.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/add-grouping.png"
                alt="Hover over Created At and click on the plus button to add a grouping by month. You can select other time intervals (day, week, year) by clicking on by month."
              />
            </p>

            <p>As soon as you add the grouping, Metabase updates the chart:</p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/sum-total-by-month.png"
                alt="The sum of order totals by month."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              This chart is a lot easier to read. And, of course, we can always
              select a section of the line to filter the results for that time
              period, and drill through to see those individual, unaggregated
              records.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/drill-through.gif"
                alt="Zooming in and drilling through a line chart to view individual records."
              />
            </p>

            <h2 id="customizing-your-line-chart">
              Customizing your line chart
            </h2>

            <p>
              To customize your line chart, you can click on the <strong
                >Settings</strong
              > button in the bottom left. There are too many settings to cover here
              without boring you, so well just give you some highlights.
            </p>

            <h3 id="display-tab">Display tab</h3>

            <p>
              The <strong>Display tab</strong> lets you change the line color and
              style, handle missing values, and so on. If you plan on embedding your
              chart in your app, check out our <a
                href="/docs/latest/configuring-metabase/appearance"
                >white labeling option</a
              > for even more customization.
            </p>

            <h4 id="trend-lines-and-goal-lines">Trend lines and goal lines</h4>

            <p>
              You can add a trend line from the display settings of a time
              series chart. Youll see the toggle if youve chosen exactly one
              time field from <strong>Summarize</strong> &gt; <strong
                >Group by</strong
              >. In the example below, weve chosen the grouping field Created
              At: Month:
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/goal-and-trend-line.png"
                alt="Line chart with goal and trend lines."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              You can also add a goal line to plot a horizontal line at your
              goal value. Goal lines are especially useful when paired with
              alerts. For example, if youre monitoring sales, and you only want
              to get notified if a metric dips below a certain threshold, you
              can add a goal line to specify that threshold and get an email or
              have a Slack message sent when the line goes under it.
            </p>

            <h4 id="line-area-or-bar-chart">Line, area, or bar chart?</h4>

            <p>
              Weve been talking strictly about line charts so far, but <a
                href="/learn/metabase-basics/querying-and-dashboards/visualization/bar-charts"
                >bar charts</a
              > and area charts are similar, and there are good reasons to choose
              them instead of a line chart, depending on what youre trying to communicate:
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/area-chart.png"
                alt="An area chart."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              Area charts are typically used to compare values over time. If you
              dont have that many values plotted over time, consider a bar
              chart. If you want to see the composition of values over time, use
              a stacked bar chart.
            </p>

            <p>
              You can also combine line and area charts in a <a
                href="/docs/latest/questions/visualizations/combo-chart"
                >combo chart</a
              > to visualize different aggregations, like the count and sum of order
              totals shown below. We discuss combo charts in more detail <a
                href="/docs/latest/questions/visualizations/visualizing-results#combo-charts"
                >here</a
              >.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/total-and-count.png"
                alt="The count of orders as a blue line, set against the green area chart plotting the sum of order totals."
              />
            </p>

            <h3 id="axes-tab">Axes tab</h3>

            <p>
              Here you can adjust the scale of the x and y axes. For the x axis,
              you can select either time series or ordinal scales. Time series
              will limit the number of values displayed, whereas the ordinal
              scale will list each value in the series along the x axis. Use an
              ordinal scale if youre plotting steps in a sequence.
            </p>

            <p>
              For the y axis, you can select linear (the default), or power or
              log scales. Logarithmic scales are great for showing the rate of
              change over time, especially when your data has an exponential
              rise or decay.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/log-scale.png"
                alt="The log scale view of the sum of order totals by month shows us that the growth in totals has flattened out over time."
              />
            </p>

            <p>
              And you can probably just ignore power scales, as no one really
              uses them.
            </p>

            <h2 id="line-chart-tips">Line chart tips</h2>

            <p>
              Metabase takes care of a lot of the best practices for visualizing
              data for you, but here are some tips to keep in mind when creating
              line charts.
            </p>

            <h3 id="pair-a-line-chart-with-a-trend-chart">
              Pair a line chart with a trend chart
            </h3>

            <p>
              When creating a dashboard, you can pair a line chart with a <a
                href="/docs/latest/questions/visualizations/visualizing-results#trends"
                >Trend</a
              > chart to make the latest value easy to read.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/dashboard-with-trend-and-line-charts.png"
                alt="Pair a line chart with a trend chart to show the latest number."
              />
            </p>

            <h3 id="hover-over-a-label-to-highlight-a-line">
              Hover over a label to highlight a line
            </h3>

            <p>
              You can hover over the name of one of your series in the legend to
              highlight it and make the others fade out. You can also click on a
              series to hide (or unhide) it.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/hover-to-highlight-line.gif"
                alt="Hovering over labels in the legend hill highlight the corresponding line."
              />
            </p>

            <h3
              id="for-time-series-filter-out-any-time-period-still-in-progress"
            >
              For time series, filter out any time period still in progress
            </h3>

            <p>
              When dealing with time series, your charts can look nicer if you
              add a filter to exclude the day, week, or month thats currently
              in progress; otherwise your chart will have a huge drop on the far
              right because of the partial or incomplete time period. Just
              uncheck the <strong>Include this day</strong> or week, month, or whatever
              time scale youre working with.
            </p>

            <p>
              <img
                src="/learn/images/line-charts/filter-include.png"
                alt="Unless you really need the most recent (and potentially incomplete) period of time, make sure the Include this... option isn"
              />
            </p>

